properties.name: Barringer (Canyon Diablo)
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobN 35° 2\', W 111° 1\'When most people think of meteor craters, they think of... Meteor Crater, or Canyon Diablo, or the Barringer Crater. This was formed perhaps 49,000 years ago when an object slightly smaller than a bus hit the ancient Arizona countryside.

properties.name: Beach Across From Carlin Ponds Park, Jupiter
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob  This huge expanse of white sand is a great place to just throw down an old blanket and watch meteor showers, count the stars, observe satellites... quite a bit, actually!

properties.name: Best Part Of Youth 1976 - 1980
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob1701 East Hawaii Drive, 32246Mom married my Dad (and he is my Dad) in May 1976, and we moved here. For the first time in my young life, I found stability. This is where the best years of my childhood were spent. As I became a teenager, I had many more... escapades... here. If the washroom could talk....

properties.name: Coral Cover Park, Tequesta
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobThink of this as Blowing Rocks (which is just up the road a piece) little sibling. There is a fantastic coral and limestone outcrop here; great for snorkeling. But, of course, we\'re talking astronomy here. Good all round observing spot.

properties.name: County Dock & Mandarin Boardwalk
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobCounty Dock & Mandarin BoardwalkOnce upon a time, the St. John\'s River was a thriving waterway, and this dock harkens back to those days. Nice for west and northwesterly views from the boat ramp (but be aware of the tides!), or binocular viewing from the dock itself.

properties.name: Dyer Park, West Palm Beach (On Top Of The Mound!)
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob  Once upon a time, this was a landfill. Now, it\'s a pretty big park with an extensive network of bicycle trails. The mound stands perhaps 7 meters (22 feet) above the park, and is an excellent place to set up or just relax with a pair of binoculars.

properties.name: Fort Caroline
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob  I first went here in the summer of 1969, shortly after my family returned home. No point in going into the history of the site, since the link will do a better job. Suffice to say, except for a five year period, I have spent at least one day every year (usually around Easter) at the fort. Introduced my godson to it today (25th March \'06). He\'s my legacy, I want him to have this as his.

properties.name: Griffith Observatory & The Aldrin Planetarium, South Florida Science Museum
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob  Not that I would actually be doing any Vagabonding here; Kind of fond of the place, really (trust me!). The Griffith Observatory is home to a 14" Celestron.

properties.name: Hobe Sound Nature Center, Hobe Sound
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob While not as perfectly suited for astronomy as Jonathan Dickinson State Park, this little facility has enoug space in the parking lot to hold a little event.

properties.name: Home, 1980 - 1983 (And An Observation...)
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob1953 East Indies Dr, 32246Lived here from February 1980 to September 1983, when I lost my mind and married at the age of 20. But that\'s not what I want to point out. Instead, I want to draw your attention to the subdivision to the east. It looks like a diagram of the large intestines drawn by Picasso. That used to be my forest... so sad. If you zoom in and compare those houses to the humble little house I lived in, you\'ll see that they are enormous. But they have no yards. We\'ve become a nation of shut-ins...

properties.name: Jupiter Nature Park
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob This little park is located off of US 1 between Jupiter and Juno, Florida. Coastal scrub environment, one of the few areas like it that is still "open" as opposed to "private" (I do so hate "No Trespassing" signs...). I decided to check this place out in the late spring of \'01, forgot to hydrate, and spent the next 24 hours in the hospital due to dehydration! Those trails are actually maze-like; be sure to bring water.

properties.name: Jupiter Ridge Nature Park
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob Probably one of the few places left in this area that preserves the sensitive nature of the Florida scrub environment in close proximity to large suburban areas. The parking lot should be ideal for setting up any number of scopes!

properties.name: Lookout at Theodore Roosevelt Hiking Area
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob Ever stood on the edge of a saltwater marsh and just... listened? During the windy seasons (spring and fall), the marsh grass has a magical quality as the wind whistles through it. Plenty of waterbirds make this and nearby Tiger Creek home. But just go out there and stand... listen... watch...

properties.name: Losco Regional Park
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob There are a number of soccer fields here, but on nights when they are not in use, this field is pretty good for a lot of astronomy. As with most city parks, it closes at 10PM.

properties.name: Mandarin Park
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobI lament the passing of the old Mandarin. When I was growing up there in the 1970\'s, it was more like this than the hustle and bustle along SR-13... what they call San Jose Boulevard these days. This gives you a pretty good cross section of forests, from oak paddocks to turkey oak forests. Incidentally, turkey oaks (quercis laevis) is my favorite tree, but is considered a waste tree by some, so too often in the past they\'d be simply removed. Pity, since there is a strange magic in turkey oak forests.

properties.name: Manicouagan
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobN 51° 23\', W 68° 42\'This is a very ancient impact (better than 24 million years), and it has left a sizable scar upon the face of our planet, 100km (62.5 miles) across. Notice how far you have to zoom out to see it completely.

properties.name: Mike Roess Goldhead Branch State Park
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob This is one of those magical places that has remained thankfully unchanged since my childhood. Came here for the first time in May of 1975 with my best friend Craig Buffkin and his family; his birthday. Really loved the place right from the start. There are a number of lakes, a ravine (yes, Florida has ravines), and some of the nicest forests you have ever seen. But look at the satellite image for a second. Look at the spacing of those trees. Most of Goldhead is covered with turkey oaks. When you\'re flying along I-95 south towards Orlando, you\'re seeing woodlands that are artificially thick due to "management". Most forests in Florida would manage themselves, usually through fires. The reason that they are so thick in places is due to letting growth continue in an unnatural fashion. Fires are actually part of the life cycle of forests, God\'s way of keeping things in check. Those turkey oaks (plus some pines) are another example of how Florida should look. Great place. Get there early, stay there late, camp. Walk the trails, enjoy this patch of north Florida.

properties.name: My Heartbreak
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob1604 Davidson Street, 32207Back in 1992, my then wife and I bought this house. As our marriage unravled, so did the payments, and in March of 1998, we lost the house. Still very special, and now lovingly cared for.

properties.name: Odessa
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobN 31° 45\', W 102° 29\'While not as old as Canyon Diablo/Barringer (perhaps as recently as 20,000 years), this crater lacks the same degree of definition. This is due to the fact that the iron meteor that created it was not nearly as large, perhaps less than 10 tonnes, or the size of a car (though obviously not the weight). Over time, this small crater has simply weathered and filled. Erosion has made most astroblems almost invisible.

properties.name: Okeeheelee Park, West Palm Beach
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob  This park blows me away! So many places to choose from. Once upon a time, this was a pretty large country club. Now, it is one of the premier parks here. The marker is on a hill overlooking the lake network, an excellent spot.

properties.name: Our Story Begins Here
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobMartin, KentuckyWasn\'t supposed to be born here. Mom went to Kentucky to visit some family members, and the little bun-in-the-oven-that\'d-be-me wasn\'t due until January. Suffice to say, on 3rd December, 1962... ta da...

properties.name: Parking Lot At Books-a-Million
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobThe Parking Lot In Front Of Books-a-MillionTypical suburban mall parking lot... so we\'re limited to planetary and lunar observing most nights. But Books-a-Million is open until 11PM Monday through Saturday, and 9PM on Sundays... good if you want to grab a cup of Joe!

properties.name: Sidewalk & Seawall, Castillo De San Marco
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobA wonderful reminder of Florida\'s heritage, Castillo de San Marco was built in the late 17th century as the main defense for the Spanish settlement. This is a great site for sidewalk astronomy, if only for the ambience.

properties.name: Tennis Courts At Mandarin Park
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob  Since no one really plays tennis there at night (and the place does close at 10 pm), this is an alternate site for viewing. Not as unpleasant to walk on.

properties.name: The Beach At Big Talbot Island
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob  This is another example of a Florida that once was. As you move south along Florida\'s east coast, the flora changes. This section of the coast line has more in common with beaches northwards into the Carolinas, with stands of oaks almost to the water\'s edge. This beach is truly wonderful, with all that snow white sand. Inland, you\'ll find salt marshes plentiful.

properties.name: The Field At Mandarin Park
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobField At Mandarin ParkA bit darker than most of the surrounding area, better for many objects but with a slightly more restricted field of viewing. Park is open until 10pm most nights.

properties.name: The Old Cox Abode
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob1856 Jefferson Road, Jacksonville, FloridaMy grandparents, Grace and Elmer Cox, moved here in the early 1960\'s. This was their property. I lived on this property sporadically from 1969 to 1974; kind of wish we still owned it.

properties.name: The best used book store
properties.description: Posted by SomedaysolingJacksonville Florida

properties.name: This Is Nine Mile Road...
properties.description: Posted by AstrorobNine Mile Road, St. John\'s CountyIn the name of crass commercialization, the road was renamed International Golf Parkway. In reality, it only has anything to do with golf once it crosses Interstate 95. This little stretch of it is how coastal northeast Florida should look. Stunning in the spring time.

properties.name: Tree Hill Nature Center
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob Imagine a nature center of this quality right in the center of the crowded Arlington section of Jacksonville. I first went here in the spring of 1976, and it left an immediate impression; it seemed so out of place, but there it was, tucked into suburbia. I went on to do volunteer work here in 1991. If you get a chance, swing on by and check this wonderful place out. Some of the grandest live oaks you will ever see, ancient grape vines bigger around then your arm, two genuine Florida upland creeks. Take your kids or yourself and see what Florida is really like.

properties.name: Westside Regional Park
properties.description: Posted by Astrorob While there is a small field, this is not a bad place for some observing. At least it gives the folks at NAS a nearby spot.
